-## 10. Change log
+## 10. Why this clone diverges from Screaming Frog's shape
+
+Screaming Frog (SF) is the inspiration for the crawl semantics and audit rules, but it is a different *kind* of product. SF is a single-user desktop application: a Swing + JavaFX UI bolted to a crawler core, persisting each project to an embedded Apache Derby database that lives inside a `.seospider` file on the user's local disk. One process, one user, one tenant, one filesystem. Scheduling is in-process; CLI mode (`--headless`) is just the same JVM started without a window. (See `screamingfrog1/REVERSE_ENGINEERING_NOTES.md` for the storage + flow details.)
+
+This clone is, by design, the opposite shape: a multi-tenant SaaS. Concretely:
+
+- **Storage.** Postgres (per-tenant rows, `tenant_id` on every table) replaces embedded Derby. Redis backs the queue and rate limiter. There is no `.seospider` file format and no per-user local DB.
+- **Frontend.** A separate React SPA, served as a static bundle, talks to the Rust API over HTTPS+JSON. SF's Swing tables and JavaFX `HtmlDiffViewer` become an API endpoint (`GET /v1/.../html-diff`) plus a planned SPA viewer — same diff semantics, different transport.
+- **API surface.** Axum HTTP + JWT auth. Every request is tenant-scoped; SF has no equivalent because it has no concept of "another user."
+- **Scheduling.** SF's in-process scheduler becomes a job system (slice 6.6): rows in `scheduled_jobs`, a worker that enqueues crawls on cron, run history per tenant. There is no `--headless` flag — running unattended is the default mode for the worker.
+- **Deployment.** EC2 instances pulling images from ECR, deployed via SSM. SF ships as a signed JVM installer.
+
+Out of scope on purpose: license/activation parity (SF has a paid license + activation server; this clone integrates with Laravel for billing instead), and the exact byte layout of `.seospider` files. We reuse SF's *crawl behavior* and *audit rule set*, not its packaging or distribution model.
+
